<main id = "main">
<h1 id = "title">Walter Pitts: A Professional Taught by a Library</h1>
  <figure id= "img-div">
    <img 
      id = "image scr=" src="https://i2.wp.com/mindhacks-legacy.s3.amazonaws.com/2005/08/walter_pitts.jpg?zoom=2"
         alt= "Walter Pitts leaning on a desk."
 />
    </figure>
    <h3 id="headline">A brief history of one of the most rebel scholars ever:</h3>
    <section>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>1923</strong>
        - Born in Detroit, Michigan to Walter and Marie.
      </li>
      <li>
  <strong>1935</strong> 
     - At the age of 12, Walter spent three days in the library reading Principia Mathematica, wrote a letter to Bertrand Russell, and was invited to go to college.
      </li>
      <li>
 <strong>1938</strong>
    - At the age of 15, he attended lectures, met his close friend Jerome Lettvin, studied logic with Rudolf Carnap. Carnap helped Pitts study logic, which Pitts mastered.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>1942</strong>
        - He went to live with Warren McCulloch and, while living with him, led to them collaborating on writing a nerural network paper called "A Logical Calculus of Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity". The paper lead Warren to be called the second father or A.I. 
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>During 1943-1944</strong> - He was a graduate student in Physics at MIT.
      </li> 
      <li>
        <strong>1951</strong> - Pitts and other physiologists of the nervious system were hired by Norbert Wiener. 
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>1952</strong> - Weiner broke off his relations to Pitts and others.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>During 1956-1958</strong> - He was a graduate student in the electrical engineering and computer science department.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>1959</strong> - He burned his unpublished doctoral dissertation that had years of undocumented work.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>1965</strong> - He produced a paper on olfaction with Lettvin and Robert Gesteland.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>1969</strong> Pitts died of bleeding esophageal varices.
        </li>
    </ul>
       <blockquote
      cite="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Pitts"
    >
      <p id="tribute-info">
        "in no uncertain sense the genius of the group â€¦ when you asked him a question, you would get back a whole textbook."
      </p>
      <cite>-- Lettvin's evaluation of Pitts</cite>
    </blockquote>
       <h3>
      Please check out more about the life of this unrecognized genius on
      <a
        id="tribute-link"
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Pitts"
        target="_blank"
        >Wikipedia entry</a
      >.
    </h3>
  </section>
